@page "/insights/articles/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit"
@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly
@using BlazorDX.Demo.Client.Insights

<PageTitle>The Architecture of Silence — BlazorDX Insights</PageTitle>

<EditorialLayout Kicker="Article" Title="The Architecture of Silence"
                 Subtitle="Inside the Zero-Trust Ephemeral Chat Conduit: a server that never sees plaintext, a browser-sandboxed crypto core, and a closed room that tears itself down the moment it's disturbed."
                 Published="new DateOnly(2026, 7, 17)" ReadingMinutes="7"
                 HeroImageSrc="images/insights/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit/sanctuary-hero.jpg"
                 HeroImageAlt="A lone figure works at a minimalist, geometric desk lit from within, in an empty room overlooking a city skyline at dusk."
                 FooterCards="footerCards">

    <EditorialFigure Caption="A message travels from provider to browser as a single unbroken thread — the router in between never touches what passes through it.">
        <img src="images/insights/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit/transparent-connection.jpg"
             alt="Two figures in profile face each other, connected by a single strand of light passing from one to the other." loading="lazy" />
    </EditorialFigure>

    <div class="dx-editorial-body">
        <p>
            Most chat features start from the same question: how do we store this conversation
            safely? The Ephemeral Chat Conduit starts from a different one — what if, for certain
            messages, the right answer is <em>we don't store it at all</em>? Not "we delete it
            later." Not "we encrypt it at rest." We never hold a copy in the first place, and the
            server that carries it never has the ability to read it.
        </p>
        <p>
            That's a harder engineering problem than it sounds, because a server that routes a
            message usually has to understand a little about it — who it's for, whether it's still
            valid, when to stop delivering it. The Conduit's answer is to give up that
            understanding entirely, and push everything that requires trust into two much smaller,
            much more inspectable places: a browser-sandboxed decryption step, and a DOM node built
            to notice when it's being tampered with.
        </p>
    </div>

    <EditorialSidebar Title="What 'zero-trust' means here" Icon="🔒">
        Not a marketing gloss — a structural claim. The server component,
        <code>BlazorDX.Conduit</code>, documents itself as a <strong>blind router</strong>: every
        payload and event it forwards is opaque bytes it never parses, inspects, or decrypts. If
        the server is compromised, an attacker gets ciphertext they can't read — not because of a
        policy, but because the code that would let them read it doesn't exist on that machine.
        <span class="dx-editorial-sidebar-caveat">
            This describes message confidentiality in transit through the router. It is not a
            claim about authorization — see the sidebar further down.
        </span>
    </EditorialSidebar>

    <EditorialScrollytelling Intro="Four steps, four trust boundaries. Scroll to follow one message through the pipeline.">
        <EditorialScrollyStage Index="01" Title="A provider encrypts, once" Glyph="✉">
            Before a message reaches BlazorDX at all, the MCP resource-provider that owns it
            encrypts it. The Conduit never receives plaintext — there's no point in the pipeline
            where it could, even if you wanted it to.
        </EditorialScrollyStage>

        <EditorialScrollyStage Index="02" Title="The Conduit relays blind" Glyph="↯">
            <code>BlazorDX.Conduit</code> pushes the ciphertext to the browser over Server-Sent
            Events — a <code>PAYLOAD</code> event, alongside <code>WITHDRAW</code> and
            <code>REFRESH</code> for revocation and rotation. The relay is best-effort: if nobody's
            listening when an event fires, it's simply gone. No queue, no replay, no guaranteed
            delivery — a deliberate trade against ever holding state that could leak.
        </EditorialScrollyStage>

        <EditorialScrollyStage Index="03" Title="The browser decrypts, alone" Glyph="🔑">
            A Rust crate compiled to WebAssembly (<code>dx_security</code>) runs the actual
            handshake — P-256 ECDH, then AES-256-GCM — entirely inside the browser's own sandbox.
            No hardware enclave, no secure element; this is an ordinary wasm module, isolated the
            same way any browser tab is isolated from any other. The private key material never
            crosses back to the server, and it never touches JavaScript's garbage-collected heap.
        </EditorialScrollyStage>

        <EditorialScrollyStage Index="04" Title="A closed room, self-aware" Glyph="◈">
            The decrypted text is written — via <code>textContent</code>, never
            <code>innerHTML</code> — into a <strong>closed-mode Shadow DOM</strong> node: a part of
            the page that JavaScript outside that exact closure genuinely cannot read back out. A
            <code>MutationObserver</code> watches it continuously; the instant something tries to
            alter it from outside, the node tears itself down.
        </EditorialScrollyStage>
    </EditorialScrollytelling>

    <div class="dx-editorial-body">
        <p>
            That last step is the one worth sitting with. A closed shadow root isn't a convention
            or a lint rule — it's a real boundary the DOM API enforces: code holding a reference to
            the host element cannot reach into a closed shadow tree. Combined with never using
            <code>innerHTML</code> for the payload, the message text can't leak sideways into a
            script that wasn't meant to see it, even a script running on the same page. This
            specific property — no plaintext in the initial server-rendered HTML, no light-DOM
            leak from a closed root — is something we didn't just design for. It's covered by an
            end-to-end Playwright test that renders the real component and inspects the actual DOM.
        </p>
    </div>

    <EditorialFigure Caption="Enclosed by its own boundary: what's inside is visible through the glass, but nothing outside can reach in and touch it.">
        <img src="images/insights/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit/sovereignty-over-self.jpg"
             alt="A figure works at a lit surface inside a glass dome, streams of light passing by outside the glass without entering." loading="lazy" />
    </EditorialFigure>

    <EditorialPullQuote Attribution="From the Conduit's own design notes">
        A router that cannot read what it routes cannot be made to leak it — by policy, by bug, or
        by subpoena.
    </EditorialPullQuote>

    <EditorialSidebar Title="The client-side state machine" Icon="◐">
        <p>The Blazor component (<code>SecureEphemeralChat</code>) tracks a small, real FSM as the message moves through its life:</p>
        <dl>
            <dt>Decrypting</dt><dd>Handshake and AES-GCM decrypt in progress inside the wasm module.</dd>
            <dt>Mounted</dt><dd>Plaintext is live in the closed shadow root.</dd>
            <dt>Withdrawn</dt><dd>The provider revoked it, or the observer caught tampering — content is gone.</dd>
            <dt>Failed</dt><dd>Handshake or decrypt failed; nothing was ever mounted.</dd>
        </dl>
    </EditorialSidebar>

    <EditorialSidebar Title="What this doesn't claim" Icon="⚠">
        <p>Two gaps worth naming plainly, because a "zero-trust" label invites exactly that kind of scrutiny:</p>
        <p><strong>No authorization ships by default.</strong> Deciding who's allowed to open a
        session is an explicit extension point (<code>IEphemeralSessionAuthorizer</code>) a host
        application must implement — the Conduit doesn't gate access on its own out of the box.</p>
        <p><strong>Delivery is best-effort, not guaranteed.</strong> The SSE transport has no
        replay and no queuing. A disconnected client simply misses a <code>WITHDRAW</code> or
        <code>REFRESH</code> event; there's no retry.</p>
    </EditorialSidebar>

    <EditorialScrollytelling Intro="One more stage — the moment a message stops existing.">
        <EditorialScrollyStage Index="05" Title="Deliberate impermanence" Glyph="○">
            When a session ends, the Rust module zeroizes the buffer holding the plaintext, and the
            browser bridge overwrites the shadow-root text node before removing it. We're
            deliberately not calling this a <em>proof</em> of anything. It's a best-effort erasure:
            the code's own comments say plainly that overwriting a JavaScript string cannot
            guarantee the original heap bytes are gone — the runtime doesn't give you that
            guarantee to keep. What we can and do verify is narrower and more honest: that the
            content is unreachable through the API surface a consumer of this component actually
            has.
            <EditorialDissipation AriaLabel="An illustration of a message's on-screen presence dissolving once its session ends." />
        </EditorialScrollyStage>
    </EditorialScrollytelling>

    <EditorialFigure Caption="The moment a session ends: a buffer is zeroized, a node is overwritten, and the light goes out — not because it's magic, but because nothing on the other side kept a copy.">
        <img src="images/insights/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit/right-to-erasure.jpg"
             alt="A hand closes a glowing laptop-like panel, the light dimming as it shuts." loading="lazy" />
    </EditorialFigure>

    <div class="dx-editorial-body">
        <h2>Why build it this way</h2>
        <p>
            None of this is about distrust of any particular server operator. It's about not
            asking anyone to trust one at all for the specific, narrow case of a message that was
            only ever meant to exist for a moment — an authorization code, a one-time credential, a
            piece of context an AI agent needed once and shouldn't retain. The architecture doesn't
            make a promise about the server's intentions. It makes the server unable to break the
            promise, structurally, whatever its intentions turn out to be.
        </p>
        <p>
            BlazorDX is a beta library with no production deployments yet, and this feature is one
            of its newest, least battle-tested pieces — that's true of the whole project, and we'd
            rather say it here than have you discover it. What's real today: the crypto primitives
            are standard and auditable (P-256, AES-256-GCM), the blind-routing design is enforced
            by what the server code can and can't do, and the closed-shadow-DOM isolation is
            covered by a real, running end-to-end test — not just a design doc. What's still ahead:
            authorization is a bring-your-own extension point, not a default; and a full production
            deployment needs a real broker round-trip this repository doesn't yet implement end to
            end.
        </p>
    </div>

    <EditorialFigure Caption="The point was never distrust. It was building an architecture that doesn't ask anyone to keep a promise it could accidentally break.">
        <img src="images/insights/zero-trust-ephemeral-chat-conduit/freedom-from-digital-footprints.jpg"
             alt="A figure stands in an open field at dusk, releasing a stream of light particles into the sky." loading="lazy" />
    </EditorialFigure>
</EditorialLayout>

